            <mi>t</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>−<!-- − --></mo>
        <mi>P</mi>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\text{Discount}}=P(1+r)^{t}-P.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/fb8660bf1296e7afa06808dc4579a073aa1329f5" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:26.787ex; height:3.009ex;" alt="{\displaystyle {\text{Discount}}=P(1+r)^{t}-P.}"></span><sup id="cite_ref-Economics_Discount_2-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Economics_Discount-2"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<p>We wish to calculate the <a href="/wiki/Present_value" title="Present value">present value</a>, also known as the "discounted value" of a payment. Note that a payment made in the future is worth less than the same payment made today which could immediately be deposited into a bank account and earn interest, or invest in other assets. Hence we must discount future payments. Consider a payment <i>F</i> that is to be made <i>t</i> years in the future, we calculate the present value as 
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle P={\frac {F}{(1+r)^{t}}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>P</mi>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mi>F</mi>
            <mrow>
              <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
              <mn>1</mn>
              <mo>+</mo>
              <mi>r</mi>
              <msup>
                <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mi>t</mi>
                </mrow>
              </msup>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle P={\frac {F}{(1+r)^{t}}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/8536e1bbd55053f3734731eccfcfc318adb3f2d0" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.671ex; width:13.367ex; height:6.009ex;" alt="{\displaystyle P={\frac {F}{(1+r)^{t}}}}"></span><sup id="cite_ref-Economics_Discount_2-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Economics_Discount-2"><span class="cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class="cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<p>Suppose that we wanted to find the present value, denoted <i>PV</i> of $100 that will be received in five years time. If the interest rate <i>r</i> is 12% per year then
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext="{\displaystyle {\rm {PV}}={\frac {\$100}{(1+0.12)^{5}}}=\$56.74.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
